{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6ac35666-75d5-4066-9eae-8a292eca7da4","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile, collected directly inside the pod.\n\n### Quick steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Exec into the pod\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- /bin/bash\n\n# 2. Install the tool (if not already in the image)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n\n# 3. Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 4. Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can copy out and open in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (use `--format speedscope` for browser-based viewing).\n\n### Tips\n- **No restart needed** — `dotnet-trace` attaches to the live process via EventPipe.\n- For **off-CPU analysis** or native stacks, use `dotnet-trace collect --profile cpu-sampling --clrevents gc+gchandle` or consider `perf` / `dotnet-counters` first to narrow the problem.\n- Copy the trace out: `kubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace`\n- If the container lacks the .NET SDK, you can use the [global tool standalone install](https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace) or a sidecar/debug container.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9cbaa051-616d-48a1-aeeb-de8591f67292","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":428},"id":"3783caf9-7c55-4e36-9f27-6fe7a6729e68","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:53:29.126Z","parentId":"d7ea2f6c-5779-4088-bf49-67f09a8c4c30"}
